14. Standardize each predictor by subtracting its mean and dividing by its standard deviation (i.e., so each predictor is centered with unit variance). Regress distance on each of the standardized predictors. Provide a table that ranks the predictors based on the size of the regression coefficients. The larger the size, the more important the predictor. Store the results in a new table, called Table 3; be sure to include a third column giving the sign of the corresponding coefficient.

# Assuming filtered_data is already loaded and prepared

# Convert factor variables with only one level to numeric
filtered_data <- filtered_data %>%
  mutate(across(where(~ is.factor(.) && nlevels(.) == 1), as.numeric))

# Standardize numeric columns
numeric_columns <- sapply(filtered_data, is.numeric)

FAA_Stand <- data.frame(scale(filtered_data[numeric_columns]))
names(FAA_Stand) <- names(filtered_data)[numeric_columns]

# Add 'distance' column back if it's numeric and was scaled
if (numeric_columns["distance"]) {
    FAA_Stand$distance <- filtered_data$distance
}

# Perform linear regression for each standardized predictor
model_stand <- lapply(names(FAA_Stand)[names(FAA_Stand) != "distance"], function(var) {
    lm(as.formula(paste("distance ~", var)), data = FAA_Stand)
})

# Extract coefficients
coef <- sapply(model_stand, function(m) coef(m)[2])

# Create Table 3
table3 <- data.frame(Variable = names(coef), Coefficient = coef)
table3 <- table3 %>% arrange(desc(abs(Coefficient))) %>% mutate(coef_direction = ifelse(Coefficient < 0, "-ve", "+ve"))

# Display Table 3

17. Suppose in Table , the variable ranking is as follows: X1, X2, X3, X4, X5, and X6, where X1 and X6 are the most important and least important predictors, respectively. Please fit the following six models

# Assuming 'filtered_data' is already loaded and prepared

# Standardize numeric columns
numeric_columns <- sapply(filtered_data, is.numeric)
FAA_Stand <- data.frame(scale(filtered_data[numeric_columns]))
names(FAA_Stand) <- names(filtered_data)[numeric_columns]

# Add 'distance' column back if it's numeric and was scaled
if (numeric_columns["distance"]) {
    FAA_Stand$distance <- filtered_data$distance
}

# Include non-numeric variables (like 'aircraft') in FAA_Stand
FAA_Stand$aircraft <- filtered_data$aircraft

# Now proceed with your linear regression models
var_selection <- c()

var_selection[1] <- summary(lm(distance ~ speed_ground , data = FAA_Stand))$r.squared     
var_selection[2] <- summary(lm(distance ~ speed_ground + aircraft, data = FAA_Stand))$r.squared 
var_selection[3] <- summary(lm(distance ~ speed_ground + aircraft + height, data = FAA_Stand))$r.squared
var_selection[4] <- summary(lm(distance ~ speed_ground + aircraft + height + duration, data = FAA_Stand))$r.squared
var_selection[5] <- summary(lm(distance ~ speed_ground + aircraft + height + duration + pitch, data = FAA_Stand))$r.squared
var_selection[6] <- summary(lm(distance ~ speed_ground + aircraft + height + duration + pitch + no_pasg, data = FAA_Stand))$r.squared

parameters <- c(1:6)

var_selection_result <- data.frame(parameters, var_selection)
print(var_selection_result)

Part VII: Variable selection using automatic search procedures

21.Use the R function StepAIC() from package MASS to perform forward variable selection; see ?MASS:stepAIC for details and usage examples (or ask in the class Teams chat). Compare the result with those from 19).

library(MASS)
## Warning: package 'MASS' was built under R version 4.3.2
## 
## Attaching package: 'MASS'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     select
FAA_Stand_Imputed <- FAA_Stand
numeric_columns <- sapply(FAA_Stand_Imputed, is.numeric)
FAA_Stand_Imputed[numeric_columns] <- lapply(FAA_Stand_Imputed[numeric_columns], function(x) ifelse(is.na(x), mean(x, na.rm = TRUE), x))

# Start with the minimal model (only intercept)
start_model <- lm(distance ~ 1, data = FAA_Stand_Imputed)

# Perform forward selection
forward_model <- stepAIC(start_model, scope = list(lower = start_model, upper = lm(distance ~ ., data = FAA_Stand_Imputed)), direction = "forward")

By incorporating these additional steps, we ensure a more comprehensive analysis that not only selects predictors effectively but also validates and evaluates the model thoroughly.

Part VIII. The Mirage of variable selection

Variable selection requires spending information from the system in order to make decisions on what variable to keep. However, the root problem is that the Probability of selecting the right variables is 0, unless you have millions upon millions observations and not too many candidate variables.

So you can also get a false negative where variables that are not selected turns out to be important and vice versa.Frank also mentioned that it is very uncommon for someone to replicate feature selection and have the same results as the work they try to replicate.

Frank mentioned that if your goal is pure prediction, having variable selection is not important. However, the most stable model selection method he recommends is full flexible Bayesian model with carefully chosen shinkage priors.
